<h2>Reviewing for O'Reilly</h2>

<p>For my first review as part of the O’Reilly Reader Review Program I chose <em>Lean UX</em> by <a href="http://www.jeffgothelf.com/blog/ " target="_blank">Jeff Gothelf</a>, with <a href="http://www.joshuaseiden.com/" target="_blank">Josh Seiden</a>.</p>
<figure><a href="http://oreilly.com/bloggers/?cmp=ex-orm-blgr-daniel-furze" target="_blank"><img alt="I review for the O'Reilly Reader Review Program" src="http://cdn.oreillystatic.com/bloggers/blogger-review-badge-200.png"></a></figure>
<p>I'd not heard of these authors before my encounter with the program and hadn't read any books on or delved very deeply into <em>Lean</em> at all - in fact I chose <em>Lean UX</em> over an HTML5 book and an iOS development book mainly because I had no real prior knowledge of Lean and wanted to challenge myself for my first O’Reilly bloggers post.</p>
<p>As well as this, I currently work in an Agile software development company, <a href="http://codeweavers.net" target="_blank">Codeweavers</a>, and I enjoy working in an environment like this but I’ve not read into the methodologies behind it too much before and having heard Lean mentioned by some of the operations team alongside agile I became interested in this title when I saw it on offer. </p>

<h2>Lean for beginners?</h2>
<p>Jeff Gothelf, thankfully, introduces Lean to the absolute novice (such as myself) in the first section of his book - <strong>Introduction and Principles</strong> - explaining simply what it is, who it is for and what we may hope to achieve from reading the book.</p>
<p>The outlining of the Lean principles in the first chapter and relating them to agile development already had me making copious amounts of highlights and notes, ready to compare and contrast them with the workflow and processes that we undertake at Codeweavers.</p>
<p>The language at this point is simple and friendly enough for me as something of a beginner in this area to grasp and the author gives excellent examples within every principle showing “what it is” and “why do it”.</p>

<h2>Lean Processes</h2>
<p>Leading the reader into the second section of <em>Lean UX</em> - <strong>Process</strong> - with a completely relatable anecdote, Jeff then goes on to give a step by step breakdown of each part of the Lean process for the start of a project along with methods that could be easily applied to many projects our teams have undertaken in the past and are in the midst of currently too.</p>
<p>Many more anecdotes, diagrams and even printable worksheets serve as great resources to anyone wanting to implement an amount of Lean processes into their workflow after reading this book. </p>
<figure>
  <img src="http://static.furzeface.com/img/blog/28/lean_ux_diagrams.jpg" alt="Lean UX diagrams and drawings"/>
  <figcaption>Throughout the book, many diagrams help explain the processes.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Throughout the early <strong>Process</strong> chapters, there is a constant reiteration of the core values of Lean in relation to a design team and their processes and Jeff really tries to get across the notion of change and the positive aspects that it will bring to any company wishing to undertake them. </p>
<p>If any reader was to note down the steps that he gives in these chapters I surmise that they’d have all that they need to start revolutionising the way that they work right away!</p>

<h2>Style Guides</h2>
<p>There’s an emphasis on personas and style guides in this part of the book - two excellent sounding tools that we should utilise more of when designing and developing customer facing user interfaces. I won't go into what exactly they are here, (read the book!) but just to say that they're both extremely useful tools.</p>
<p>I’ve had great positive experiences with creating living style guides for freelance projects I’ve undertaken that have been built collaboratively with others and it’s good to see in the case studies that large companies are taking the time to use them to their full potential  - something that I hope to implement for larger scale projects at my workplace if possible in the future.</p>
