<h2>Digging into it...</h2>
<p>The further I got into <em>Lean UX</em>, the more I realised that I could relate to the principles shown, not just in my place of work but in every project I’m involved in. </p>
<p>At first I thought that was down to the fact that as I mentioned before I work in an agile company, but the concepts are explained so clearly that I believe that someone even more of a novice than I would be able to take Jeff’s advice on board and hopefully use it to make the case to their employer of using Lean principles in relation to user experience design.</p>

<p>The chapter on <strong><abbr title="Minimum Viable Products">MVPs</abbr></strong> grabbed my attention - listing the forms of prototype to be used whilst designing a new product and I instantly found myself imagining the uses for them and wanting to know if there was any prototyping software the authors could recommend.</p>
<p>On turning (swiping?) the page I found such a list waiting for me! Jeff Gothelf and Josh Seiden don’t leave anything out in this book!</p>
<p>The next chapter, <strong>Feedback and Research</strong>, was exceptionally interesting as I read this bit whilst at work around the time that we’d got a bit of feedback on a project and I was making some slight changes in order to enhance the usability of our app.</p>
<p>The author goes on to explain methods of feedback and research along with why and how frequently you should be undertaking them. I’ve been reading a lot about user testing recently and the book gave me a lot more to think about when talking about integrating it into the workflow.</p>

<h2>Making Lean UX Work</h2>
<p>Now, since skimming an overview of this book before I intended to read it, I was quite excited for the final chapters.</p>
<p>Jeff talks in the final section of Lean UX about how to integrate it into an agile workflow and environment as well as giving advice on the shifts a company would have to make in order to do so.</p>
<p>I’m not saying that I’ll be able to integrate these ideas into the workflow we currently have at Codeweavers but I shall hopefully be able to take some of the ideas on board when scoping out a new project or <abbr title="Minimum Marketable Feature - our version of an MVP">MMF</abbr> and I’m hopeful that some of the things described on this book will come naturally to me and other members of the design team from now on.</p>

<p>I won’t give too much away about these final parts but I’ll say that once again, Jeff and Josh succeed in explaining the vital pieces of the Lean UX puzzle to anyone without much prior knowledge.</p>
<p>The use of relatable case studies contribute to an easy to understand, thorough, exceptionally well-written guide to implementing Lean UX.</p>
